    <item>
      <title>The Funding Two-Step and Possibly More Cabinet Confirmations</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/476/2025-02-10_the-funding-two-step-and-possibly-more-cabinet-confirmations</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/476/2025-02-10_the-funding-two-step-and-possibly-more-cabinet-confirmations</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2025 17:40:50 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Good morning, Govtrekkers,&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House and Senate are in this week. Much of the work is happening behind the scenes, with the two major focuses of work being budget reconciliation and appropriations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Budget reconciliation&lt;/strong&gt; is a &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/98-814.html"&gt;two-step process&lt;/a&gt; by which the House and Senate coordinate a legislative package that can address spending, revenue, and the debt limit. Crucially, it allows the Senate to bypass the filibuster and pass legislation by a 51-vote margin. Republicans are wrangling over whether to do one budget reconciliation resolution or two and what should be included in the legislation. This matters because the coalition necessary to pass this legislation may break apart over disagreements about the more difficult matters that may be deferred to a second budget reconciliation resolution.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;One big question: whether and how to address the debt ceiling. The debt ceiling was hit on January 17th, and it is only a matter of time before the government will be forced to shut down unless Congress grants additional authority to pay the obligations the government already has incurred. As &lt;em&gt;Roll Call&lt;/em&gt; recently reported, Republicans &lt;a href="https://rollcall.com/2025/02/09/johnson-budget-blueprint-not-ready-for-prime-time/"&gt;have not yet reached an agreement&lt;/a&gt; on the framework to move a resolution forward.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Appropriations&lt;/strong&gt; is another thorny issue. Congress should have enacted spending bills for Fiscal Year 2025, which began October 1, 2024, but instead they passed a Continuing Resolution (often called a “CR”). It kept the prior year’s funding level and runs out on March 14th. By that date, Congress will have to pass the FY 2025 appropriations bills or another CR. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;For &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/live-updates/2025/02/07/congress/shutdown-vibe-check-00203185"&gt;reasons&lt;/a&gt; that range from disagreements within the Republican conference about spending priorities to the administration’s unlawful use of impoundment — when the White House refuses to spend funds as directed by Congress — senior Appropriators have not been able to reach agreement on top line funding levels. These top line numbers determine how much money is available for defense versus non-defense appropriations spending, and also break out how much money is available for each of the twelve appropriations subcommittees to spend.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Democrats have some leverage in this process. Because of the filibuster, passing an appropriations bill in the Senate requires sixty votes, and there are only fifty-three Republicans. In the House, it is fairly likely that some Republicans will not vote with Republican leadership on the spending bills, so Democratic support will be necessary to move legislation in that chamber. Unsurprisingly, some Democrats are unwilling to support a process unless it addresses &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2025/02/09/kim-trump-government-shutdown-00203267"&gt;Democratic concerns&lt;/a&gt; about White House efforts to “dismantle the government.” Republicans may have sufficient differences of opinion that even with control of both chambers they cannot do it on their own.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The major legislative action in Congress this week&lt;/strong&gt; are votes on Trump’s cabinet nominees. The timing of when the floor votes occur is unclear, like most things in the Senate. It is likely that we will see votes on Tulsi Gabbard to serve as director of National Intelligence and Robert F. Kennedy to lead Health and Human Services. We also may see votes on Howard Lutnick to serve as head of the Department of Commerce, Brooke Rollings as secretary of Agriculture, and Kelly Loeffler as head of the Small Business Administration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House does not have any major legislation &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;scheduled for the floor&lt;/a&gt;. There are two comparatively minor bills scheduled for a vote pursuant to a rule (needing only a simple majority) and a half-dozen suspension bills (needing a 2/3rds majority).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/02/10"&gt;34 committee meetings&lt;/a&gt; scheduled across the two chambers, including a few appropriations hearings in the House. Some committees are still holding their organizational meetings. Senate Labor will hold a nomination hearing on the Secretary of Labor, Senate Judiciary will hold a nomination hearing on the nomination of Kash Patel to be FBI Director, and Senate Health will hold a hearing on the nomination of Linda McMahon to be Secretary of Education. The House Judiciary Committee will hold a hearing on “reining in the administrative state” and the House Foreign Affairs Committee will look at “the USAID betrayal.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House Administration Committee will hold two hearings on funding levels for House committees. If you’re interested in diving deep into how House Committees are funded, I wrote about it in my other newsletter, the &lt;em&gt;First Branch Forecast&lt;/em&gt;, in an article entitled &lt;a href="https://firstbranchforecast.substack.com/p/insider-threat"&gt;insider threat&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>More Cabinet Confirmations; House Filling Time</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/475/2025-02-07_more-cabinet-confirmations-house-filling-time</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/475/2025-02-07_more-cabinet-confirmations-house-filling-time</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 07 Feb 2025 17:24:10 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;The Senate continued to confirm cabinet positions for the new administration while the House has been filling time with miscellaneous bills. The real focus among House Republicans - a Repbulican-only reconciliation bill or bills - remains largely behind the scenes. Another possible government shutdown is now five weeks away.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Cabinet Confirmations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;For more information about each nominee, see &lt;a href="https://apnews.com/projects/trump-cabinet-confirmation-tracker/"&gt;AP's tracker&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;Wright, Secretary of Energy, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s30"&gt;59-38&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Collins, Secretary of Veterans Affairs, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s32"&gt;77-23&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Bondi, Attorney General, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s33"&gt;54-46&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Turner, Secretary of Housing and Urban Development, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s35"&gt;55-44&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Vought, Director of the Office of Management and Budget, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s37"&gt;53-47&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;House Bills&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr43"&gt;H.R. 43: Alaska Native Village Municipal Lands Restoration Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h28"&gt;412-1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr776"&gt;H.R. 776: Nutria Eradication and Control Reauthorization Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h29"&gt;361-56&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr27"&gt;H.R. 27: HALT Fentanyl Act&lt;/a&gt;, which is another of the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hres5/text/eh#link=5_b_11_%7ET1&amp;amp;nearest=H4E49B7F18928402A87C17E094583E485"&gt;Republican priority bills&lt;/a&gt; listed in the House Rules, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h33"&gt;312-108&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>More Confirmation Votes; More Republican Priority Bills</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/474/2025-02-03_more-confirmation-votes-more-republican-priority-bills</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/474/2025-02-03_more-confirmation-votes-more-republican-priority-bills</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 03 Feb 2025 14:23:04 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Hey there Govtrekkers,&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Both the House and Senate are in this week. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On Tuesday, the House starts its &lt;a href="https://docs.house.gov/floor/"&gt;legislative business&lt;/a&gt; at 6:30 pm, with eight presumably non-controversial bills to be considered and which will take a 2/3s vote of the chamber to pass. The House routinely schedules evening votes to force members back to town for work the next day.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;These bills concern Native Americans, museums, a report on using aircraft to suppress wildfires, conveying federal land to a municipality, and the elimination of an invasive rodent.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On Wednesday and for however long they keep at it, the House has two bills scheduled which only require a simple majority vote to pass. The first bill is the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr27"&gt;HALT Fentanyl Act&lt;/a&gt;. It appears identical to the same named &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr467"&gt;bill from the 118th Congress&lt;/a&gt;, and would permanently schedule all fentanyl-related substances as schedule I under the controlled substances act. That legislation passed the House 289-133. The Biden administration issued a &lt;a href="https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/statement-administration-policy-hr-467-halt-all-lethal-trafficking-halt-fentanyl-act"&gt;statement of administration policy&lt;/a&gt; in support of the legislation. The Senate never took up the bill. More than one hundred House Democrats had &lt;a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/antoniopequenoiv/2023/05/25/why-a-bill-called-the-halt-fentanyl-act-has-some-lawmakers-split/"&gt;voted against the legislation&lt;/a&gt; out of concern “it could lead to unjustified incarcerations and stifle research involving the drug for purposes like treating pain from cancer.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The second bill is the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr26"&gt;Protecting American Energy Production Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would prohibit any president from declaring a moratorium on the use of hydraulic fracturing. It appears to be identical to &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr1121"&gt;legislation that passed the House&lt;/a&gt; last Congress 229-188, but was not taken up in the Senate. The Biden administration issued a &lt;a href="https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/statement-administration-policy-hr-1121-protecting-american-energy-production-act"&gt;statement of administration policy&lt;/a&gt; in opposition to the legislation, writing: the bill “is both unnecessary and would set a dangerous precedent for limiting the authority of the President and Secretary of the Interior to manage energy resources on Federal lands and waters”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House has &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/02/03?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22House%22%7D"&gt;fifteen hearings&lt;/a&gt; scheduled this week. The most high profile may be a hearing on “rightsizing government,” timely as the Trump administration moves to fire a large number of federal workers. Another hearing asserts California fires are the result of overregulation, several hearings attack the former Biden administration for various reasons, and there’s a hearing on federally funded research involving animals.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As usual, the Senate has not given much indication of what legislation it will consider on the floor. However, we can expect the Senate to &lt;a href="https://www.democrats.senate.gov/2025/01/30/schedule-for-monday-february-3-2025"&gt;try to move forward&lt;/a&gt; the nominations of Pam Bondi to be Attorney General; Eric Turner to be Secretary of Housing and Urban Development; Russell Vought to be director of the Office of Management and Budget; and Christopher Wright to be Secretary of Energy. The uncertainty arises because we do not know how the Senate Majority Leader will prioritize particular nominations, whether some Republicans may withhold support for particular nominees; and what Democrats do to try to slow down the vote or stop the nominees.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Proceedings are scheduled for &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/02/03?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22Senate%22%7D"&gt;nine committees&lt;/a&gt;. The only nomination hearing scheduled for next week is Jamieson Greer to be US Trade Representative. Armed Services and Intelligence both have closed proceedings. The Senate Judiciary Committee will hold a hearing on fentanyl. The Commerce Committee will hold a markup on a long list of bills and the Committee on Small Business will markup a few bills. Senate Banking will hold a hearing on debanking.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In the background, Republicans held a retreat this past week to figure out how they can fast track their priorities through budget reconciliation. Meanwhile, the continuing resolution for federal spending runs out in six weeks and the federal government is already using extraordinary measures to avoid hitting the debt ceiling.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Cabinet Confirmations</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/473/2025-01-31_cabinet-confirmations</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/473/2025-01-31_cabinet-confirmations</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 31 Jan 2025 16:24:25 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;This week's post will be a short one. The House Republicans spent the first part of the week in a retreat and held no votes in the rest of the week. The Senate has held a number of hearings on cabinet nominees and begun to vote on them. &lt;a href="https://apnews.com/projects/trump-cabinet-confirmation-tracker/"&gt;The AP has a handy tracker&lt;/a&gt; that includes a little information about each nominee / confirmed cabinet member.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Confirmed Cabinet Positions&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;Bessent - Treasury Secretary - &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s19"&gt;68-29&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Hegseth - Secretary of Defense - &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s15"&gt;51-50&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Duffy - Secretary of Transportation - &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s21"&gt;77-22&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Burgum - Secretary of the Interior - &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s26"&gt;79-18&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Rubio - Secretary of State - &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s8"&gt;99-0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Ratcliffe - Director of the Central Intelligence Agency - &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s13"&gt;74-25&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Zeldin - Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency - &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s24"&gt;56-42&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Noem - Secretary of Homeland Security - &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s17"&gt;59-34&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;See you all next week.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Legislative Grab Bag; Two Cabinet Confirmations</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/472/2025-01-24_legislative-grab-bag-two-cabinet-confirmations</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/472/2025-01-24_legislative-grab-bag-two-cabinet-confirmations</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 24 Jan 2025 15:49:48 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;This week one bill completed the process to pass both chambers and will be signed soon by President Trump. The House passed a number of other bills, most with Democratic support and the Senate confirmed the first two cabinet positions for the new administration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Laken Riley Act&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s5"&gt;S. 5: Laken Riley Act&lt;/a&gt; passed the House this week &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h23"&gt;263-156&lt;/a&gt;. It goes to the President next for signing.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Other Legislation&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr165"&gt;H.R. 165: Wounded Knee Massacre Memorial and Sacred Site Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would reduce taxes on the relevant land, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h22"&gt;416-0&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr187"&gt;H.R. 187: MAPWaters Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt;, which would "provide for the standardization, consolidation, and publication of data relating to public outdoor recreational use of Federal waterways among Federal land and water management agencies", passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h19"&gt;413-0&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr375"&gt;H.R. 375: Continued Rapid Ohia Death Response Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt;, which would continue to provide support for efforts to address a disease affecting native trees in Hawaii, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h24"&gt;359-62&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;H.R. 471: Fix Our Forests Act](&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr47"&gt;https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr47&lt;/a&gt;), which would primarily allow logging companies to bypass environmental reviews, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h25"&gt;279-141&lt;/a&gt;. There are a number of provisions in the bill and differing attitudes towards its central provisions. &lt;a href="https://oregoncapitalchronicle.com/2024/10/11/oregons-congressional-members-sharply-divided-over-bill-to-step-up-logging-to-prevent-wildfires/"&gt;The Oregon Capital Chronicle&lt;/a&gt; provides a good overview of the bill's contents.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Republican Priority Legislation&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;In the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hres5/text/eh#link=5_a_%7ET1&amp;amp;nearest=HCF4279D4F89845B7947163E919CDA0DC"&gt;House Rules resolution&lt;/a&gt; for the 119th Congress, Republicans listed twelve pieces of legislation they considered the highest priority for passage. So far, they've passed six of them; all with Democratic support, although not necessarily much Democratic support. The Laken Riley Act noted above covers two of the priority bills after an amendment added by the Senate. This week, they added one more (the sixth of twelve) with the&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr21"&gt;H.R. 21: Born-Alive Abortion Survivors Protection Act&lt;/a&gt; which would require health care providers to provide care for any fetus that survived an attempted abortion, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h27"&gt;217-204&lt;/a&gt;. One Democrat, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/henry_cuellar/400657"&gt;Rep. Henry Cuellar (D-TX28)&lt;/a&gt; voted in support of the bill. This bill has come up repeatedly in the last decade. &lt;a href="https://www.factcheck.org/2019/03/the-facts-on-the-born-alive-debate/"&gt;This article from Fact Check&lt;/a&gt; notes that reports of this situation are extraordinarily rare. Some states go years without a single instance reported despite tens of thousands of abortions.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Trump Cabinet Confirmations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;So far, two Cabinet nominees have been confirmed: &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s8"&gt;Marco Rubio for Secretary of State&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s13"&gt;John Ratcliffe for Director of the Central Intelligence Agency&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Stay The Course: New GovTrack capabilities and government accountability's outlook</title>
      <author>Joshua Tauberer       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/471/2025-01-22_stay-the-course-new-govtrack-capabilities-and-government-accountabilitys-outlook</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/471/2025-01-22_stay-the-course-new-govtrack-capabilities-and-government-accountabilitys-outlook</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 23 Jan 2025 02:23:20 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Hi everyone. Today you're hearing from Josh, the founder of GovTrack. I'm writing for two reasons. First, we have some new features on the site that you may find useful. Second, I have a more dire note about the last decade's trajectory in government accountability.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;New on GovTrack&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Our newest feature is &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/missing"&gt;Missing Legislators&lt;/a&gt;. Last year former Rep. Kay Granger managed to &lt;a href="https://www.notus.org/congress/kay-granger-republican-majority"&gt;disappear from Congress&lt;/a&gt; for five months. That should never happen again, and that's why we built Missing Legislators to see at a glance if any legislators have missed a large number of recent votes. We &lt;a href="https://mastodon.social/@GovTrack"&gt;post to social media&lt;/a&gt; every time a legislator is added to the list. Check on it to be sure your representatives don't make the list.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the vote search page, you can now &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes#session=308&amp;amp;sort=uniformity"&gt;sort votes from least to most party uniformity&lt;/a&gt;. Some votes also have a new table showing how the vote &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h136"&gt;breaks down by congressional caucuses&lt;/a&gt;, which gives insight into the factions and blocs in Congress. And you can &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts.rss"&gt;subscribe to an RSS feed of these very updates&lt;/a&gt; if that's your thing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We've been &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/press"&gt;in the news&lt;/a&gt; lately: We &lt;a href="https://www.cnbc.com/video/2024/12/31/congress-passes-only-503-bills-one-of-the-least-productive-in-decades.html"&gt;appeared on CNBC&lt;/a&gt; to talk about what Congress accomplished and the outlook for 2025. NBC News used our data to write about &lt;a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/data-graphics/congress-age-2025-third-oldest-us-history-rcna185742"&gt;Congress getting older&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href="https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2024/12/23/texas-rep-kay-granger-missed-majority-of-us-house-votes-this-year/"&gt;The Dallas Morning News&lt;/a&gt; mentioned us in their article about Rep. Granger. And new &lt;a href="https://www.psypost.org/congress-members-less-outspoken-against-covid-19-policies-after-personal-infections-study-finds/"&gt;research used our database&lt;/a&gt; of legislators who got COVID.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;A dire outlook&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;There is some more good news before I get to the bad news: Congress is getting more transparent about its day-to-day activities.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In the last decade, &lt;a href="http://congress.gov"&gt;Congress.gov&lt;/a&gt; has become a modern and sophisticated legislative research tool, the House now usually gives a week of advanced notice on bills being considered and committee schedules, committee meetings are now all streamed online, historical records are being digitized, and on. The best part is that nonpartisan staff regularly meet with us and other congressional transparency organizations to include us in charting the path forward. There is a beacon of light there. (It's no accident the beacon exists. It's something we advocated for.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The rest isn't good.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In Congress, bills are getting cobbled together in last-minute huge omnibus deals that are nearly impossible to read (a problem that's been getting worse over the last decade). The &lt;a href="https://firstbranchforecast.substack.com/p/the-new-years-eve-ethics-massacre"&gt;ethics committees are often rubber-stamps&lt;/a&gt;. The Senate still gives few clues about upcoming votes. Committee votes are still hard to find. Legislators are ceding more power to the executive branch and Big Tech. And, frankly, many legislators are simply not being serious.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Outside of Congress, in the executive branch, well, it's been &lt;a href="https://governing.digital/2022/12/09/response-to-the-proposed-themes-for-a-5th-u-s-national-action-plan-on-open-government/"&gt;a long time since a president made any effort&lt;/a&gt; to create a more transparent government or shut the revolving door of corporate lobbyists. The Biden Administration waited for its last days to issue &lt;a href="https://civic-texts.ghost.io/good-news-for-the-open-social-web-and-open-government-data/"&gt;an executive order implementing an open data law&lt;/a&gt; enacted six years ago --- it was too little too late. The Supreme Court won't address its appearance of wild impropriety. (I wish somebody would send me on secret trips to elite resorts too! I promise it won't affect my judgment.) The media, both "mainstream" and "social," has given up on standing up to power as they drown us in an expanding stream of homogenizing bullshit (forgive my language). Generative AI is making it worse. And we know what to expect for the Trump Administration's position on transparency and accountability since we've been here before.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are &lt;a href="https://www.thebulwark.com/p/open-government-nonprofits-are-dying-off-just-when-needed-most"&gt;few organizations like ours left&lt;/a&gt;. It's dire. It's really dire.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I don't have a positive note to end on, and I don't know what to do. The trajectory of the last decade for transparency, accountability, and democracy will be hard to turn around.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But we're not going anywhere. Stand with us. Stay the course.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>News About GovTrack</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Votes, Missing Members and Nomination Hearings</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/470/2025-01-17_votes-missing-members-and-nomination-hearings</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/470/2025-01-17_votes-missing-members-and-nomination-hearings</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 17 Jan 2025 14:11:03 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;h2&gt;Transparency and Disaster Assistance&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Most votes this week were overwhelmingly approved.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr153"&gt;H.R. 153: Post-Disaster Assistance Online Accountability Act&lt;/a&gt; which would "provide for an online repository for certain reporting requirements for recipients of Federal disaster assistance" passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h10"&gt;426-0&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr144"&gt;H.R. 144: Tennessee Valley Authority Salary Transparency Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would require the publication of salaries of executives of the Tennessee Valley Authority, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h14"&gt;423-0&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr192"&gt;H.R. 192: Amtrak Executive Bonus Disclosure Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h8"&gt;407-0&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr33"&gt;H.R. 33: To amend the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 to provide special rules for the taxation of certain residents of Taiwan with income from sources within the United States&lt;/a&gt;, which is intended to provide tax relief for some residents of Taiwan, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h15"&gt;423-1&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr164"&gt;H.R. 164: POWER Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt;, which would permit federal agencies to provide additional assistance after a disaster, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h13"&gt;419-2&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr152"&gt;H.R. 152: Federal Disaster Assistance Coordination Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would fund a study to improve information collection and damage assessments after a disaster, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h9"&gt;405-5&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Banning Transgender Athletes&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr28"&gt;H.R. 28: Protection of Women and Girls in Sports Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt;, which would bar federal funding from any school K-post-secondary that allows trans girls/women athletes, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h12"&gt;218-206&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Immigration&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr30"&gt;H.R. 30: Preventing Violence Against Women by Illegal Aliens Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would "amend the Immigration and Nationality Act to provide that aliens who have been convicted of or who have committed sex offenses or domestic violence are inadmissible and deportable", passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h17"&gt;274-145&lt;/a&gt;. The &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2025/01/16/us/house-bill-deport-immigrants.html"&gt;New York Times reports&lt;/a&gt;, "existing law already allows immigrants with contested legal status who are convicted of sex crimes to be deported".&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s5"&gt;S. 5: Laken Riley Act&lt;/a&gt; continues to work through the Senate. Last week, Democratic Senators said they were voting to move forward on the bill in order to improve it by amendment. So far this week, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s3"&gt;Democrats voted for an amendment to expand its scope&lt;/a&gt;, but &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s4"&gt;Republicans did not vote for an amendment to remove its most far-reaching provision&lt;/a&gt; which would give states substantial new authority over immigration policy. Today, Democrats can, if they're unhappy enough with how the amendment process went, prevent the bill from coming to the floor by refusing to vote to end debate.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Missing Members&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;After the news at the end of December that former Rep. Kay Granger had missed several months of votes, due it appears to &lt;a href="https://www.texastribune.org/2024/12/22/texas-kay-granger-health-fort-worth/"&gt;significant and never disclosed health problems&lt;/a&gt;, we set up an alert for ourselves and our users to try and prevent such lengthy absences from slipping past again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This week we were alerted that several CA legislators had missed votes last week, presumably because  of the wildfires around Los Angeles.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Rep. Nancy Pelosi (D-CA11) also missed some votes, presumably because she's still recovering from fracturing her hip in late December.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When we can, we'll try to find out why someone might be out and note it in our recaps and on the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/missing"&gt;Missing Legislators&lt;/a&gt; page.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Nomination Hearings&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;There were about a dozen committee hearings for cabinet nominees for President-elect Trump's next term this week. We watched some where we could, but if there's an agency or nominee of particular interest to you that you missed, you can still watch the recordings. Go to &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/01/13"&gt;Congress.gov's Committee Meetings&lt;/a&gt; calendar and look for the one you want.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Votes on the nominees will start sometime next week. Only a simple majority is needed and there are enough Republicans to get a simple majority even for nominees who do not have Democratic support. Of the nominees with hearings so far, all appear likely to be confirmed, possibly with some Democratic votes.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
