      <title>Kristi Noem for Homeland Secretary and Sean Duffy for Transportation</title>
      <author>Jesse Rifkin       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/469/2025-01-15_kristi-noem-for-homeland-secretary-and-sean-duffy-for-transportation</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/469/2025-01-15_kristi-noem-for-homeland-secretary-and-sean-duffy-for-transportation</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 15 Jan 2025 14:07:35 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Today we have the last two of our series on former Congressmembers nominated for President-elect Trump's cabinet. We've combined them because we want to get them to you in time and still keep up our legislative recap posts while not inundating everyone's inbox. Noem's hearing will be on &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/senate-event/336506?s=1&amp;amp;r=28"&gt;Friday, Jan. 17&lt;/a&gt; and Duffy's is &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/senate-event/336508?s=1&amp;amp;r=10"&gt;today, Jan. 15 at 10 am EST&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;If you don't see this until after the hearings, the recordings are generally available to watch later at the same link as with &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/senate-event/336480?s=1&amp;amp;r=1"&gt;Pete Hegseth's hearing yesterday&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr&gt; &lt;h3&gt;How did Trump’s Homeland Security Secretary nominee Kristi Noem vote in Congress?&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/kristi_noem/412475"&gt;Former Rep. Kristi Noem (R-SD0)&lt;/a&gt;, now governor of South Dakota, is President-elect Donald Trump’s pick to replace &lt;a href="https://www.dhs.gov/keywords/secretary-alejandro-mayorkas"&gt;Alejandro Mayorkas&lt;/a&gt; as Secretary of Homeland Security. The position requires confirmation by the Senate.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her home state lies 1,500 miles from the Mexico border. But she’s made a name for herself in part through border policies, including &lt;a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2024/11/29/noem-national-guard-border/"&gt;deploying her state’s National Guard to the border&lt;/a&gt; with Mexico three times, frequent &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=826GeNuTLD4&amp;amp;pp=ygUUS3Jpc3RpIE5vZW0gRm94IE5ld3M%3D"&gt;Fox News appearances&lt;/a&gt; to discuss the issue, and famously declaring to her legislature: &lt;a href="https://news.sd.gov/news?id=news_kb_article_view&amp;amp;sysparm_article=KB0041679"&gt;“Every state is now a border state.”&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Department of Homeland Security contains the border and immigration agencies ICE, CBP, USCIS, TSA, and the &lt;a href="https://www.gocoastguard.com/about#:%7E:text=The%20U.S.%20Coast%20Guard%20is,the%20Department%20of%20Homeland%20Security."&gt;Coast Guard&lt;/a&gt;, as well as the Secret Service, the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, and FEMA which handles emergency and disaster relief.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2024/12/04/noem-fema-south-dakota-floods/"&gt;Some South Dakota residents say&lt;/a&gt; that Noem as governor has done a poor job managing June’s floods in the state.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Noem served in Congress from 2011 to 2018.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h4&gt;Border wall funding&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;In Congress, Noem &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/115-2017/h435"&gt;voted for&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/house-gop-approves-1-6-billion-trump-s-wall-n787271"&gt;$1.6 billion&lt;/a&gt; towards Trump’s border wall in July 2017, as did almost all House Republicans. Only five GOP members voted against it, while an identical five Democrats voted for it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But when that money was ultimately incorporated into a &lt;a href="https://docs.house.gov/billsthisweek/20180319/BILLS-115SAHR1625-RCP115-66.pdf"&gt;2,232-page&lt;/a&gt; government funding bill in March 2018, Noem voted against it. That bill divided House Republicans, who supported it by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/115-2018/h127"&gt;145-90&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;GOP supporters hailed the border wall funding and other conservative measures – after all, Republicans controlled both congressional chambers at the time. But most Republican opponents &lt;a href="https://www.texastribune.org/2018/03/22/us-house-passes-13-trillion-spending-bill-includes-some-border-wall-fu/"&gt;aligned on the party’s right wing&lt;/a&gt;, criticizing the bill for Democratic-added provisions attaching conditions to the border wall funding, including provisions funding medical services (other than abortion) provided by Planned Parenthood.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h4&gt;Bills introduced&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;For eight years before Noem rose to national prominence as governor starting in 2019, she represented South Dakota’s lone seat in the House with comparative anonymity – and with far less policy focus on homeland security, immigration, or border issues.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She was the primary sponsor of &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?sponsor=412475"&gt;85 bills&lt;/a&gt;, almost none of which focused on homeland security, immigration, or border issues.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In fact, most of her legislation was very niche and state-specific in nature. These include bills with titles like the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr686"&gt;Protect Our Prairies Act&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr2801"&gt;Protecting Access to Rural Therapy Services Act&lt;/a&gt;, and the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr5871"&gt;Spearfish Canyon and Bismarck Lake Land Exchange Act&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;An archived version of her House.gov website from 2013 had a webpage titled &lt;a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130214033504/http://noem.house.gov/index.cfm/kristi-on-the-issues"&gt;“Kristi on the Issues,”&lt;/a&gt; which listed 11 policy issues, none of which are in the current purview of the Department of Homeland Security.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h4&gt;Native Americans&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;As governor, Noem’s relationships with South Dakota’s nine federally-recognized Native American tribes deteriorated to such a level that by May, &lt;a href="https://www.cnn.com/2024/05/22/politics/kristi-noem-tribal-lands-ban/index.html"&gt;all nine had banned her from their lands&lt;/a&gt;. But back in Congress, she introduced quite a bit of legislation promoting Native Americans or tribal issues. This included:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr6028"&gt;RESPECT Act&lt;/a&gt; to repeal a number of antiquated or racist federal laws and provisions, mostly dating from the 1800s and early 1900s. The acronym RESPECT stood for Repealing Existing Substandard Provisions Encouraging Conciliation with Tribes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;A bill to &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr1894"&gt;create an Office of Tribal Relations&lt;/a&gt; within the Department of Agriculture.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr1836"&gt;Protect Our Native Women Act&lt;/a&gt;, which aimed to crack down on domestic violence and sexual assault on tribal lands.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h4&gt;PRINT Act&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;In 2018, GovTrack &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr6031/summary#oursummary"&gt;covered&lt;/a&gt; Noem’s PRINT Act, a bill she introduced specifically to &lt;em&gt;reverse&lt;/em&gt; a Trump measure.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Trump’s Commerce Department instituted a 22% tariff on Canadian groundwood paper, often used to produce physical newspapers. While the ostensible reason was that Canada subsidized its paper industry at a level the U.S. didn’t, many believed Trump also had another unspoken motive: to punish the journalism and newspaper businesses.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Noem published an opinion column about her bill which &lt;a href="https://highlandcountypress.com/index.php/news/supporting-hometown-newspaper#gsc.tab=0"&gt;strongly defended journalism&lt;/a&gt;, in a way that’s much harder to imagine only six years later in 2024, given Republicans’ pronounced turn towards attacking media as biased and “fake news” even just since then.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The bill’s acronym PRINT stood for Protecting Rational Incentives in Newsprint Trade Act.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Ultimately, the legislation became moot, as the U.S. International Trade Commission &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/29/business/trump-tariffs-newsprint.html"&gt;reversed the Trump tariff&lt;/a&gt; later that year.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h4&gt;What Congress is saying&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Fortunately, President Trump has chosen Gov. Kristi Noem, a trusted leader and proven executive, to undertake the essential responsibility of restoring the Department’s core mission and securing the American homeland,” &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/mike_johnson/412706"&gt;Speaker Mike Johnson (R-LA4)&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://mikejohnson.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=1479"&gt;said in a press release&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Back home, Democrats in South Dakota have expressed more concerns about her border stances.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Gov.  Noem made a statement today that all of the people coming across the southern border are criminals. We don't agree," South Dakota state House top Democrat Oren Lesmeister &lt;a href="https://www.dakotanewsnow.com/2024/02/01/sd-democrats-respond-gov-noems-border-speech/"&gt;said earlier this year&lt;/a&gt;. "There are a lot of these people seeking asylum in the United States, trying to get away from poverty and other issues that they have to live and deal with everyday. There's some good people that are coming across our border."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In 2017, most Senate Democrats voted against Trump’s last Secretary of Homeland Security nominee Kirstjen Nielsen by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/115-2017/s305"&gt;11-37&lt;/a&gt;, though she was still confirmed in the Republican-led chamber. A similar result seems likely this time.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/gary_peters/412305"&gt;Sen. Gary Peters (D-MI)&lt;/a&gt;, the top Democrat on the Senate Homeland Security Committee, &lt;a href="https://x.com/priscialva/status/1866908067666776563"&gt;told CNN&lt;/a&gt; that he was "withholding judgment" on Noem’s pick.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr&gt; &lt;h3&gt;How did Trump’s Transportation Secretary nominee Sean Duffy vote in Congress?&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/sean_duffy/412488"&gt;Former Rep. Sean Duffy (R-WI7)&lt;/a&gt; is President-elect Donald Trump’s pick to replace &lt;a href="https://www.transportation.gov/meet-secretary/secretary-pete-buttigieg"&gt;Pete Buttigieg&lt;/a&gt; as Transportation Secretary. The position requires confirmation by the Senate.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Duffy served in the House from 2011 to 2019, when he resigned to &lt;a href="https://www.today.com/news/congressman-sean-duffy-resigning-due-health-complications-9th-child-t161345"&gt;take care of his ninth child, an infant with a heart defect&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;During his nine years in Congress, he was lead sponsor of &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?sponsor=412488"&gt;108 bills&lt;/a&gt;, almost none primarily related to transportation. By GovTrack’s count, by far his most common primary issue area was “finance and financial sector” at 42%. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?sponsor=412488&amp;amp;subject=5852#terms=6359"&gt;Only two of his bills were &lt;em&gt;primarily&lt;/em&gt; about transportation&lt;/a&gt;, though others may have touched on it more tangentially.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Those two bills were:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h4&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr3778"&gt;TIMBER Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;The 2015 bill would have eliminated weight limits for vehicles related to logging or other “forest products,” though not nationally – only for a specific &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr3778/text/ih#link=2_%7EQ1_m_2_D_%7ET1&amp;amp;nearest=H466C5553BE8D4E8E83391ACD1B8302BC"&gt;13-mile stretch of Wisconsin’s Interstate Route 39&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The issue was personal to Duffy, who previously &lt;a href="https://rollcall.com/2011/11/04/sean-duffy-no-stranger-to-logrolling/"&gt;worked as a lumberjack&lt;/a&gt; and whose hometown Hayward is home to the &lt;a href="https://lumberjackworldchampionships.com/"&gt;Lumberjack World Championships&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The legislation was ultimately &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr22/text/enr#link=A_I_D_1410_%7EQ1_o&amp;amp;nearest=H6F188E940C694994AE89F8939DAC2BC8"&gt;incorporated&lt;/a&gt; into the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr22"&gt;FAST (Fixing America’s Surface Transportation) Act&lt;/a&gt;. While that larger &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr22/text"&gt;490-page&lt;/a&gt; law attracted overwhelming support by both parties in both the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/114-2015/h673"&gt;House&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/114-2015/s331"&gt;Senate&lt;/a&gt;, Duffy actually &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/114-2015/h673"&gt;voted against it&lt;/a&gt;, his own provision notwithstanding.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h4&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr354"&gt;Railroad fines for blocking traffic during a shift change&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;Another 2015 bill would have fined railroad carriers $10,000 for each hour in which they blocked traffic at a crossing due to a shift change.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The bill attracted &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr354/cosponsors"&gt;two Republican cosponsors&lt;/a&gt; but never received a committee vote.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h4&gt;Thoughts on Democrats’ 2021 infrastructure law&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;In 2021, Congress enacted the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/117/hr3684"&gt;Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/117/hr3684/text"&gt;1,039-page&lt;/a&gt; law comprising &lt;a href="https://apnews.com/article/joe-biden-congress-infrastructure-bill-signing-b5b8cca843133de060778f049861b144"&gt;$1 trillion&lt;/a&gt; in infrastructure and transportation spending. The package passed on a mostly party-line vote, with almost unanimous Democratic support in both chambers, while Republicans largely rejected it by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/117-2021/s314"&gt;19-30&lt;/a&gt; in the Senate and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/117-2021/h369"&gt;13-200&lt;/a&gt; in the House.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;While Duffy was out of Congress by then, he publicly opposed the package, calling the high price tag “socialist” &lt;a href="https://dailycaller.com/2021/10/29/sean-duffy-build-back-better-biden/"&gt;in a 2021 appearance on Fox News’s &lt;em&gt;Outnumbered&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. Passing the package and the larger Biden agenda would be “catastrophic for America,” he claimed. (He didn’t elaborate on the claim.).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h4&gt;Environment&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;Transportation generates &lt;a href="https://www.epa.gov/transportation-air-pollution-and-climate-change/carbon-pollution-transportation"&gt;28%&lt;/a&gt; of U.S. greenhouse gas emissions, also known as GHGs, marking the largest such contributor of GHGs to climate change. Biden’s Transportation Department has issued a series of rules and regulations &lt;a href="https://www.transportation.gov/priorities/climate-and-sustainability/climate-action"&gt;aimed at curbing transportation emissions and pollution&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Duffy’s congressional voting record on environmental issues rated a &lt;a href="https://scorecard.lcv.org/moc/sean-duffy"&gt;lifetime 2% score&lt;/a&gt; from the League of Conservation Voters.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Why 2%? Of the 298 votes the organization marked as important environmental votes during his tenure, he actually cast what they deemed a “pro-environment” vote in five:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ol&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;A 2011 vote to &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/112-2011/h590"&gt;increase funding for Gulf Coast restoration projects in Louisiana by $1 million&lt;/a&gt;. Unusually for an environmental vote, the provision attracted a &lt;em&gt;higher&lt;/em&gt; percentage of Republican support than Democratic: 67% of House Republicans voted for it, compared to 57% of House Democrats. The measure passed, though it ultimately &lt;a href="https://scorecard.lcv.org/roll-call-vote/2011-590-gulf-coast-restoration"&gt;wasn’t included in the final larger package&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;A 2011 vote &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/112-2011/h633"&gt;against cutting more than $3 billion from a pending Interior and Environment appropriations bill&lt;/a&gt;. House Democrats unanimously opposed it by 0-179, while House Republicans were more torn, slightly voting for it by 126-105, pitting Duffy against most members of his party. The measure failed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;A 2012 vote &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/112-2012/h262"&gt;supporting several reforms to the National Flood Insurance Program&lt;/a&gt;, some of which would take environmental concerns more into account when setting rates. The vote was overwhelmingly in favor from both parties: 181-1 from House Democrats and 221-17 from House Republicans.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;A 2016 vote &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/114-2016/h570"&gt;giving $170 million to Flint, Michigan to fix its water infrastructure&lt;/a&gt;. A 2014 switch to alternative water sources &lt;a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5353852/"&gt;promoted by state officials and the governor&lt;/a&gt; seeped toxic lead into the city’s water supply. House Democrats unanimously supported the congressional bill by 183-0, while House Republicans voted majority against it by 101-141, pitting Duffy against most members of his party. The measure passed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;A 2019 vote &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/116-2019/h372"&gt;against a provision that would have impeded governmental efforts to save the endangered North Atlantic right whale&lt;/a&gt;. The provision was overwhelmingly rejected by both parties: 13-220 by House Democrats and 71-125 by House Republicans. The measure failed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ol&gt; &lt;h4&gt;What Congress is saying&lt;/h4&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sean is an excellent choice to lead DOT,” Senate Commerce and Transportation Committee top Republican &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/ted_cruz/412573"&gt;Sen. Ted Cruz (R-TX)&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://x.com/SenTedCruz/status/1866564667922858350"&gt;posted on X&lt;/a&gt;, formerly Twitter.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“His commitment to modernizing roads, bridges, and railways while advocating for equitable transportation funding resonates with Americans who often feel left behind by federal priorities skewed toward urban centers,” &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/marcus_molinaro/456925"&gt;Rep. Marcus Molinaro (R-NY19)&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://washingtonreporter.news/p/op-ed-rep-marc-molinaro-why-sean"&gt;wrote in a &lt;em&gt;Washington Reporter&lt;/em&gt; opinion column&lt;/a&gt;. Duffy “signals a renewed focus on bridging the transportation and infrastructure gaps that have long hindered economic growth in communities across the country.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Democrats were more cautious. While they seem likely to oppose most of his environmental stances, they haven’t explicitly condemned Duffy to the levels they have for Trump’s more controversial Cabinet nominees.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Indeed, "No specific criticism of Duffy’s nomination has emerged yet from Senate Democrats,” &lt;a href="https://enotrans.org/article/duffy-likely-to-be-confirmed-as-transportation-secretary/"&gt;the Eno Center for Transportation noted&lt;/a&gt;. “Unless something odd and unusual turns up on a background check, there probably won’t be much opposition."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Transportation policy has a long bipartisan history, and I look forward to continuing to maintain the tradition under former Rep. Sean Duffy’s leadership and working together to pass the next surface transportation authorization, creating more jobs, if he is confirmed as Secretary,” House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee top Democrat &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/rick_larsen/400232"&gt;Rep. Rick Larsen (D-WA2)&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://democrats-transportation.house.gov/news/press-releases/ranking-member-larsen-statement-on-former-representative-sean-duffys-nomination-for-department-of-transportation-secretary"&gt;said in a press release&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Analysis and Commentary</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Cabinet Nominations and Republican Priority Bills</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/468/2025-01-13_cabinet-nominations-and-republican-priority-bills</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/468/2025-01-13_cabinet-nominations-and-republican-priority-bills</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 13 Jan 2025 21:53:36 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;This week is light on legislation but heavy on hearings in the United States Senate. There are thirteen hearings for Trump’s proposed cabinet nominees out of the &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/01/13"&gt;hearings scheduled for this week&lt;/a&gt;. One of those hearings, into the Attorney General nominee, is a &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_s-ODI8He_s"&gt;two-parter&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;On Tuesday&lt;/strong&gt;, there are hearings for the nominations of former-Rep. Doug Collins to be Secretary of Veterans Affairs (&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts/465/2024-12-30_trump-veterans-affairs-nominee-doug-collins"&gt;which we wrote more about here&lt;/a&gt;), Peter Hegseth to be Secretary of Defense, and Doug Burgum to be Secretary of the Interior.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;On Wednesday&lt;/strong&gt;, there are hearings for the nominations of former Rep. Kristi Noem to be Secretary of Homeland Security (we’ll have an article about that later this week), Pamela Jo Bondi to be Attorney General, Sen. Marco Rubio to be Secretary of State (he’ll have to resign from the Senate if he’s confirmed), John Ratcliffe to be Director of the CIA, former Rep. Sean Duffy to be Secretary of Transportation (more from us forthcoming), Chris Wright to be Secretary of Energy, and Russell Vought to be Director of the White House’s Office of Management and Budget which assists the President in directing federal agencies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;On Thursday&lt;/strong&gt;, there are hearings for the nominations of Eric Scott Turner to be Secretary of Housing and Urban Development, former Rep. Lee Zeldin to be EPA Administrator (&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts/464/2024-12-28_trump-epa-administrator-nominee-lee-zeldin"&gt;which we wrote more about here&lt;/a&gt;), part two of Pamela Jo Bondi to be the Attorney General, and Scott Bessent to be Secretary of the Treasury.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the House side, I see a ton of committee organizational meetings where the committees adopt their rules for the upcoming Congress.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are a few non-nomination policy hearings in both chambers, but I expect they will be overshadowed by the pile-up in the Senate.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nine bills are lined up &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;on the House floor&lt;/a&gt; — six bills scheduled on “suspension” (the fast-track path which takes a 2/3rds vote) and three bills set for consideration pursuant to a rule which means they need only a simple majority but may have limited debate. The three bills are designed to keep Republicans together, split Democrats, and appeal to the party base. They are&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr28"&gt;H.R. 28&lt;/a&gt;, aimed at preventing trans girls and women from competing in athletics at any school from k-12 and beyond which accepts federal funding&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr30"&gt;H.R. 30&lt;/a&gt;, aimed at deporting any undocumented person who has committed a sex offense or domestic violence, and &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr33"&gt;H.R. 33&lt;/a&gt;, which concerns lessening the tax burden for investments in Taiwan, but the real target is China. A 2013 &lt;a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CRPT-118hrpt309/pdf/CRPT-118hrpt309.pdf"&gt;committee report&lt;/a&gt; on an earlier version of this bill described the purpose as to  “strengthen the U.S.-Taiwan economic alliance and improve the United States’ competitive position versus China” through “relief from double taxation on U.S.-Taiwan cross-border investment.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;Senate Republicans appear to not have updated their &lt;a href="https://www.republicanleader.senate.gov/"&gt;website&lt;/a&gt; as it indicates Sen. McConnell is still the Republican leader, so it is difficult to know their floor schedule. Nonetheless, Republicans are continuing to move their version of the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s5"&gt;Laken Riley Act&lt;/a&gt; to a vote, with the open question of whether and what amendments they will allow. That legislation would allow the federal government to take into custody unlawfully present non-citizens who have been charged with theft, which raises policy questions like whether a &lt;a href="https://immigrationforum.org/article/dreamers-in-the-united-states-an-overview-of-the-dreamer-community-and-proposed-legislation/"&gt;Dreamer&lt;/a&gt; should be deported for having been charged with but not convicted of petty crimes like shoplifting.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Happening in the background is the organizing of both chambers, with members being named to committees.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Democrats Shifting Towards Republican Positions So Far</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/467/2025-01-10_democrats-shifting-towards-republican-positions-so-far</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/467/2025-01-10_democrats-shifting-towards-republican-positions-so-far</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 10 Jan 2025 14:21:11 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;This was the end of the first full week of the 119th Congress. Much had been made before the start of this Congress of the House's very slim Republican majority which was presumed to (and may still in some cases) make it hard to pass legislation. Many journalists also noted that the new Republican Majority Leader, John Thune, said he was committing to the Senate working on Fridays which they have not been doing for quite a while.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This week, neither issue was in play. The Senate left yesterday as usual and the two bills in the House up for a vote got plenty of Democratic support which made the slim Republican majority irrelevant.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Only three bills got recorded votes in both chambers together and two were ostensibly the same bill even though there were separate Senate and House versions. Both were voted on last Congress in the House and both were on the list of 12 Republican bills given priority in the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hres5"&gt;House Rules&lt;/a&gt; which were adopted last week. Possibly ironically, the Rules passed by a much closer margin, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h5"&gt;215-209&lt;/a&gt;, than either of the bills below when presented individually.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Illegitimate Court Counteraction Act&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr23"&gt;This bill&lt;/a&gt; would "impose sanctions with respect to the International Criminal Court engaged in any effort to investigate, arrest, detain, or prosecute any protected person of the United States and its allies". In this case, it's aimed at the ICC's efforts to pursue members of the Israeli government over the war with Gaza. It passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h7"&gt;243-140&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Laken Riley Act&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr29"&gt;H.R. 29: Laken Riley Act&lt;/a&gt; passed the House &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h6"&gt;264-159&lt;/a&gt;. This bill would allow for the detention of non-citizens who are charged with certain crimes. &lt;a href="https://www.msnbc.com/opinion/msnbc-opinion/house-republicans-pass-laken-riley-act-immigration-rcna186488"&gt;Opponents of the bill note&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;The truth is that migrants arrested for crimes are already subject to detention, and there is little evidence that this law would have protected Riley, as ICE had made a previous effort to detain Ibarra.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;The bill further authorizes state attorneys general to sue the federal government if they feel that the federal government is failing to adequately enforce existing immigration laws. The consequences of the passage of this law are not yet clear, but it appears that it would change the existing model in which the federal government controls immigration policy, due to its overlap with foreign relations, to one in which states would start to exert some control over immigration policy and presumably, by extension, foreign relations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This bill passed the House last Congress as well, but was never brought up for a vote in the Senate. Now that the Senate has a Republican majority, it is already moving through Senate procedural steps with significant Democratic support. The first vote, a motion to proceed to debate, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s1"&gt;84-9&lt;/a&gt;. Next they will debate the bill, then there will be a vote to end debate and then if that passes the 60 vote threshold needed, the bill itself will receive a vote.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Next Week&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Coming up next week will be &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/01/13"&gt;the first hearings&lt;/a&gt; on President-elect Trump's cabinet nominees.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Twelve bills will be fast-tracked by Republicans' new House rules</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/466/2025-01-03_twelve-bills-will-be-fast-tracked-by-republicans-new-house-rules</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/466/2025-01-03_twelve-bills-will-be-fast-tracked-by-republicans-new-house-rules</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 03 Jan 2025 14:36:03 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Hello GovTrackers,&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Happy new year and welcome to a very special edition of the GovTrack newsletter as we get ready for the start of the 119th Congress which began Friday, January 3rd at noon, when the legislators elected last November took office.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The House of Representatives&lt;/strong&gt; voted on who will serve as Speaker of the House and on procedural rules for the chamber for the next two years. These votes are enormously consequential because they determine the playing field on which everything will happen.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I’ve written several lengthy pieces on my organization’s substack on &lt;a href="https://firstbranchforecast.substack.com/p/previewing-the-house-rules"&gt;why the House rules matter so much&lt;/a&gt; and what’s contained in the &lt;a href="https://firstbranchforecast.substack.com/p/republicans-propose-rules-for-the"&gt;House Republican rules package&lt;/a&gt;. (I also wrote about a &lt;a href="https://firstbranchforecast.substack.com/p/the-new-years-eve-ethics-massacre"&gt;sneak attack on congressional ethics&lt;/a&gt;.) They’re pretty wonky and contain a ton of detail. Let me give you the highlights.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;To fund Daniel's work tracking the House rules package you can &lt;a href="https://secure.givelively.org/donate/fund-for-constitutional-government/american-governance-institute"&gt;&lt;em&gt;donate directly to his nonprofit organization, the American Governance Institute&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (or since Daniel is also on our staff you could also &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/accounts/membership"&gt;&lt;em&gt;leave us a tip here&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;At the start of each new Congress, every two years, representatives in the House are on a level playing field: there is no Speaker, there are no committees, there are no officers of the House (like the nonpartisan Chief Administrative Officer), and all the legislation from the prior Congress disappears. They start afresh except for what’s in the Constitution and some general parliamentary principles.  So one of the first things that happens is the chamber elects a Speaker of the House and then votes on rules to govern the chamber. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Those rules create the committees and the power structure for party leaders. As I write this there’s an open question as to whether Rep. Johnson has enough votes to become Speaker. Other factions within the Republican party are negotiating for power. The form of those negotiations include both modifications to the House Rules and appointments to powerful positions, such as Chair of the House Rules Committee.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Although the Republican leadership’s proposed rules were largely a copy-paste of the rules for the 118th Congress, there are some changes. One major difference has to do with the procedure for removing the Speaker, which played a key role in the 118th Congress. Previously, any single member of Congress could bring up a resolution to remove the Speaker. Now, &lt;em&gt;nine&lt;/em&gt; Republicans have to co-sponsor such a resolution for it to be considered. This strengthens the hand of the Speaker significantly and also undermines the ability of a majority of the House of Representatives to change who is serving as Speaker.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The other major difference is that the Rules place twelve specific bills on a glide path to a vote on the House floor without allowing for hearings or amendments, by limiting debate, and waiving all the other chamber rules. (Some of these bills have already gone through committee, and fast-tracking those allows the House to pick up where it left off.) These bills are:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;For compliance with “title IX” in athletics, to define sex based solely on a person’s reproductive biology and genetics at birth (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr734"&gt;passed in 2023&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;To take into custody non-citizens who have been charged with theft.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;To make sex offenses and domestic violence deportable offenses. (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7909"&gt;passed in 2024)&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;To make the assault of a law enforcement officer a deportable offense (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr2494"&gt;passed in 2023&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;To withhold federal funding that goes to “sanctuary cities” to benefit undocumented immigrants (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr5717"&gt;passed in 2024&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;New criminal and immigration penalties for intentionally fleeing a pursuing Federal officer while operating a motor vehicle (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr5585"&gt;passed in 2024&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;To prohibit a health care practitioner from failing to exercise the proper degree of care in the case of a child who survives an abortion or attempted abortion (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr26"&gt;passed in 2023&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;To sanction the International Criminal Court for issuing an arrest warrant for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, or if it investigates, arrests, detains, or prosecutes any American or ally of the United States. (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8282"&gt;passed in 2024&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;A likely-&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr5988"&gt;bipartisan&lt;/a&gt; bill  to fix double-taxation of residents of Taiwan who pay U.S. taxes&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;To require proof of United States citizenship to register an to vote (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8281"&gt;passed in 2024&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;To amend the Controlled Substances Act with respect to the scheduling of fentanyl (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr467"&gt;passed in 2023&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;To prohibit a moratorium on the use of hydraulic fracturing (a version &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr1121"&gt;passed in 2024&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Senate is a different story&lt;/strong&gt;. It is a continuing body, so its committees and officers and rules continue from Congress to Congress. With power flipping to Republicans from Democrats, the Senate will need to pass an organizing resolution that places new senators on committees and redesignates who will serve as chairs of those committees.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In both chambers&lt;/strong&gt;, the next major legislative step will be certification of the presidential election results on Monday, January 6th. There also will likely be a resolution to allow former President Jimmy Carter to lie in state at the Capitol. It’s reasonable to expect that the certification date will put some pressure on the House Republicans to elect the Speaker relatively quickly to ensure a smooth certification of President Trump.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We also can expect to see the Senate lining up hearings and votes to confirm some of Trump’s nominees to lead various federal agencies, although the votes can’t take place before the 20th when Trump is sworn in.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;To fund Daniel's work tracking the House rules package you can &lt;a href="https://secure.givelively.org/donate/fund-for-constitutional-government/american-governance-institute"&gt;&lt;em&gt;donate directly to his nonprofit organization, the American Governance Institute&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (or since Daniel is also on our staff you could also &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/accounts/membership"&gt;&lt;em&gt;leave us a tip here&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt;      </description>
